<DOC><DOCNO> AP891215-0186 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1842EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-15 0267</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0272</SECOND><HEAD>Icy Snowstorm Spreads from Plains to East Coast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Temperatures dropped to record lows in cities across the Midwestand Great Plains on Friday as a storm dropped up to 30 inches ofsnow before moving east later in the day.   About 3 to 6 inches fell through Friday from Kansas to WestVirginia, with storm watches posted into Saturday in the Northeast.Sheridan, Wyo., got 25 inches in two days, with lesser amountselsewhere in the state and up to 18 inches in the Colorado Rockies.   At midday, snow was falling from southwestern New York state toNorth Carolina and Tennessee and as far west as Wyoming andMontana. Winter storm watches for Saturday were posted over much ofNew England, New York and northern New Jersey.   Up to 30 inches of snow fell in northeastern Wisconsin's DoorCounty in two days.   Record lows included 26 below zero at Dickinson, N.D.; 19 belowat Dubuque, Iowa; 16 below at Burlington and Carroll, Iowa andConcordia, Kan; and 15 below at Salina, Kan. Record lowtemperatures were expected to be broken again Friday night.   The low temperature for the nation Friday morning was 30 degreesbelow zero at Chadron, Neb. Temperatures around the nation at 3p.m. EST ranged from 11 degrees below zero at Lemmon, S.D., to 79degrees at Kingsville, Texas.   Snowfall during the 6 hours ending at noon included 3 inches atColumbus, Ohio, Lexington, Ky., and Zanesville, Ohio; 2 inches atAkron and Cincinnati, Ohio, Lewistown, Mont., and Pittsburgh, aswell as 1 inch at Indianapolis.</TEXT></DOC>